      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To systematically find the memory leak in your embedded C++ project, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Use a Memory Profiler**: Employ a memory profiler tool designed for embedded systems, such as Valgrind or Electric Fence, to track memory allocation and deallocation. These tools can help identify memory leaks by highlighting memory that was allocated but never freed.\n\n2. **Code Review and Static Analysis**: Conduct a thorough code review, focusing on dynamic memory allocation. Look for common pitfalls such as forgetting to free memory, using raw pointers without proper management, or creating memory leaks in third-party libraries. Tools like Clang-Tidy or Coverity can help automate this process.\n\n3. **Instrumentation and Logging**: Add logging to your code to track memory allocation and deallocation. This can help identify where the memory is being allocated and whether it is being freed correctly. Be cautious with logging in embedded systems, as excessive logging can affect performance.\n\n4. **Unit Tests and Regression Tests**: Write unit tests and regression tests for your code to ensure that memory is correctly managed. This can help catch memory leaks early in the development process.\n\n5. **Memory Allocation Patterns**: Review your memory allocation patterns. Look for areas where memory is",
