    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In embedded systems, especially when dealing with real-time tasks and interrupts, memory leaks can indeed be sneaky and challenging to track. Here are some common patterns and \"sneaky\" places where memory leaks tend to hide:\n\n1. **Static Variables**: Static variables in C++ retain their value between function calls and are not automatically cleaned up when the function returns. If you allocate memory inside a function that uses a static variable, the memory may not be freed if the function exits unexpectedly.\n\n2. **Interrupt Service Routines (ISRs)**: In embedded systems, ISRs are often used to handle asynchronous events. If you allocate memory inside an ISR, it's not automatically freed when the ISR returns, which can lead to memory leaks.\n\n3. **Dynamic Memory in Interrupt Context**: Avoid allocating memory inside ISRs. If you must allocate memory, ensure it's freed when the ISR exits. This can be tricky in real-time systems where ISRs must be as fast as possible.\n\n4. **Global Variables**: Similar to static variables, global variables are not automatically cleaned up. If you allocate memory in a global variable, it will persist for the lifetime of the program unless explicitly freed.\n\n5. **Resource Management in Real-Time Tasks**",
